        <h2>Abstract</h2>
        <p>
            Brain-Computer Interfaces are an exciting and fast evolving area where neuroscience meets technology, enabling direct communication between the brain and external devices. These systems work by detecting brain signals often using tools like electroencephalography and translating them into commands to control things like computers, robotic limbs, or other machines. BCIs were initially created to assist people with severe physical disabilities, helping them regain movement and communication. But now, the applications are broadening to include areas like gaming, mental health treatment, and even cognitive enhancement.

            At the heart of BCI technology are three main components collecting brain signals, processing those signals, and using them to control a device. In practice, this means reading brain activity, filtering out noise or interference, and then converting the signal into something a computer can understand. Every brain is different, and the signals can be weak or unclear, especially in real time use. Thankfully, machine learning and better brain imaging tools are helping improve the accuracy and responsiveness of these systems.

            As BCIs become more advanced and widespread, ethical concerns are also growing. People are starting to ask tough questions about privacy like who owns your brain data and how secure that information really is. There's also the psychological aspect how might it affect someone to control machines with their thoughts Despite these concerns, the potential is enormous. For people with disabilities, BCIs can be life changing. For others, it could open up completely new ways to interact with technology.

            In short, BCIs are at the cutting edge of science and tech. They blend biology, engineering, and ethics in a way that could transform not just how we use technology, but how we understand the brain itself.
        </p>
